<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1910-04-16T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1910-04-16T00:00:00-05:00" n="407" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d407">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 24354/2.</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Chargé <persName type="from">Monroe</persName> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Extract]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">San
                                    Jose</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1910-04-16"><hi rend="italic">April 16,
                                1910</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 1483.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to report that since
                            midnight of April 12 a series of earthquake shocks have been felt here.
                            One of them is said to have been the strongest felt since 1888. There
                            has been damage to property, but no lives have been lost. The excitement
                            was intense and continues; parks and open places are filled with tents
                            where people sleep at night. Port Limon on the Atlantic and Puntarenas
                            on the Pacific report no shocks.</p>
                        <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">G. L. Monroe</hi>,
                            Jr.</signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>